South Africa’s rand weakened against the dollar early on Tuesday, retreating from a three-week high touched last week, as rising US Treasury yields boosted the greenback. At 0645 GMT, the rand traded at 13.36 per dollar, 0.41% weaker than its overnight close. The dollar edged up on Tuesday, supported by a rise in Treasury yields following a report that US President Donald Trump was favouring a policy hawk as the next head of the Federal Reserve. South Africa’s central bank deputy governor Daniel Mminele said it was taking a cautious approach to monetary policy as risks to the inflation outlook were on the upside. Read: Sarb cautious about more rate cuts – deputy governor Stocks were set to open slightly higher at 0700 GMT, with the JSE securities exchange’s Top-40 futures index up 0.16%. In fixed income, the yield on the benchmark government bond due in 2026 was up 3 basis points at 8.67%.